06091nam a22009495i 9783110464818DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2016    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104648187 a10.1515/97831104648182doi  a(DE-B1597)462337  a(OCoLC)945752003  a(OCoLC)979733081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAW0000002bisacsh 7aLCO0000002bisacsh 7aLIT0000002bisacsh 7aLIT0120002bisacsh  aEC 54102rvk00aPerforming the Renaissance Body :bEssays on Drama, Law, and Representation /cJohn Drakakis, Sidia Fiorato. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw & Literature ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tForeword / rDrakakis, John -- tIntroduction. Performances, Regulations and Negotiations of the Renaissance Body. Legal and Social Perspectives / rFiorato, Sidia -- tI. Trying "Other" Bodies: The Witch, the Black and the Old -- t(Disciplining) Monstrous Renaissance Bodies: Staging the Witch / rNeumeier, Beate -- t"...Languished..., and then died": Courtroom Drama and the Bodies of the Victims in Thomas Pott's The Wonderfull Discoverie of Witches (1612) / rTempera, Mariangela -- tConstructing Alterity: Race, Gender, and the Body in Shakespeare's Othello / rAntor, Heinz -- tStaged and Staging Bodies as Legal and Medical sites in Volpone / rDoerr, Roxanne Barbara -- tII Codification of the Body Politic and Common Law Jurisprudence -- tRepresenting the Body of Law in Early Modern England / rRaffield, Paul -- tThe Image of Power: Shakespeare's Lord Chief Justice / rWard, Ian -- tWith Teeth and Nails: The Embodied Inservitude of Étienne de La Boétie / rBaldissone, Riccardo -- tIII. Liminal Bodies: The Life/Death Edge on Stage and in the Body Politic -- tThe Funeral Oration over Caesar's Body: Techniques of Mass Communication / rCarpi, Daniela -- tMotionless Bodies: Shakespeare's Songs for Sleep and Death / rCutolo, Raffaele -- tIV. Staging the Queenly Body: The Performance of a Female Body Politic -- tKatechontic Elizabeth: The Physical Repository of Sovereignty through Law, Literature and Iconography / rCostantini, Cristina -- tAnna of Denmark and the Performance of the Queen Consort's Sovereignty / rFiorato, Sidia -- tThe Body Politic, Female Transgression and Punishment in Jacobean Tragedy / rVelissariou, Aspasia -- tIndex  aIn the Renaissance period the body emerges as the repository of social and cultural forces and a privileged metaphor for political practices and legal codification. Due to its ambivalent expressive force, it represents the seat and the means for the performance of normative identity and at the same time of alterity. The essays of the collection address the manifold articulations of this topic, demonstrating how the inscription of the body within the discursive spheres of gender identity, sexuality, law, and politics align its materiality with discourses whose effects are themselves material. The aesthetic and performative dimension of law inform the debates on the juridical constitution of authority, as well as its reflection on the formation and the moulding of individual subjectivity. Moreover, the inherently theatrical elements of the law find an analogy in the popular theatre, where juridical practices are represented, challenged, occasionally subverted or created. The works analyzed in the volume, in their ample spectre of topics and contexts aim at demonstrating how in the Renaissance period the body was the privileged focus of the social, legal and cultural imagination.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aEuropean dramayRenaissance, 1450-1600. 0aEuropean literatureyRenaissance, 1450-1600. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aLaw and literature. 4a